{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d94566cd-be72-4f72-bc06-42480ac84864","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically captures crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Crash reports (`.ips` files)** are saved to:\n\n- `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (user apps)\n- `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (system-wide)\n\nLook for files matching your process name. You can also browse them in **Console.app → Crash Reports**.\n\n**Core dumps** are disabled by default on macOS. To enable them:\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\nsudo mkdir -p /cores && sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n```\n\nThen re-run your app — core files will appear in `/cores/`.\n\nFor the `.ips` crash log, if it involves native .NET runtime frames, you can symbolicate them using `atos` and debug symbols from the Microsoft symbol server.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"639593b5-bc50-4da5-808f-fdcb2fd7b783","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports (`.ips` files). Here's what they need to know:\n\n1. macOS automatically saves crash reports to `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user apps) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system-wide).\n2. The files have `.ips` extension (newer macOS) or `.crash` extension (older macOS).\n\n\n3. Console.app also provides a convenient way to browse crash reports directly.\n4. For actual core dumps, macOS disables them by default, but you can enable them by running `ulimit -c unlimited` and ensuring the `/cores/` directory has proper permissions.","outputTokens":433,"requestId":"7647:149CB5:E2ED1A:10A07B4:69FE9215"},"id":"7c23fa0b-a237-449f-a04b-26b3a3f5184f","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:47:14.268Z","parentId":"79b7b595-f9fd-49cf-ae87-b4aed201ffd6"}
